// ============================================================================
// GO WORKSPACE
// ============================================================================
//
// WHY: Go workspaces (introduced in Go 1.18) allow multiple modules to live
// in a single repo and reference each other without publishing to a registry.
// This is the monorepo enabler — each service is an independent module with
// its own go.mod, but `go.work` lets them import `pkg/` directly during
// development.
//
// HOW IT WORKS:
//   - `go.work` lists all modules in the workspace via `use` directives
//   - `go build`, `go test`, etc. automatically resolve inter-module imports
//     to local source instead of fetching from a remote registry
//   - Each module still has its own go.mod with proper module paths
//     (e.g., github.com/abd-ulbasit/forgepoint/pkg) for external consumers
//
// ALTERNATIVES:
//   - Go 1.17 replace directives: Fragile, each module needs replace for
//     every other module. Doesn't scale past 3-4 modules.
//   - Polyrepo: Each service in its own Git repo. Better isolation, but
//     painful cross-service refactoring, proto changes, and shared lib updates.
//   - Single go.mod monolith: All services in one module. Simple but forces
//     all services to share ALL dependencies — a Redis upgrade for one service
//     affects all services.
//
// HOW UBER/GOOGLE DO IT:
//   - Uber: Monorepo with Go workspaces (migrated from Bazel-based mono-module)
//   - Google: Monorepo (Blaze/Bazel build system, not Go modules)
//   - Buf (proto company): Uses Go workspaces for their OSS projects
//   - We follow Uber's pattern: workspace + independent modules per service
//
// NOTE: Services are added to `use()` as they're built. Start with just
// pkg (shared libs) and auth (first service).

go 1.26.0

use (
	./pkg
)
